'''''Religious Experience Reconsidered''''' is a book by [[Ann Taves]] on the study of [[religious experience]]. She proposes a new approach, which takes into account the [[attribution (psychology)|attribution]] of religious meaning to specific events, using the term "specialness."<ref name="Princeton">[http://press.princeton.edu/titles/9060.html Princeton University Press, ''Religious Experience Reconsidered'']</ref> "The focus of the book is on experiences deemed religious (and, by extension, other things considered special) rather than "religious experience.""<ref name="Princeton"/>

==Reception==
Kim Knott calls Taves approach an encompassing framework, which can take into account a multitude of things. She doubts, though, if the term "specialness" can replace the term "sacredness."{{sfn|Knott|2010}}

